post_text:
Ascension Public Schools is conducting a district-wide fundraiser to support the Calcasieu Parish School Board. Our friends in Southwest Louisiana sustained substantial damage at 97% of its schools from Hurricane Laura. We in Ascension know how hard it is to recover from a natural disaster, and we want to help!

Our schools will be communicating about dress down days in the next couple of weeks, and the district will also be collecting general donations at https://osp.osmsinc.com/AscensionLA/, click on "Central Office" then "Donations."

100% of donations will go directly to Calcasieu Parish Schools. Thank you for sharing and supporting in any way you are comfortable - even if it is with encouraging words. #AscensionStrong #CalcasieuStrong

ASCENSION PUBLIC SCHOOLS IS LOOKING
FOR SUBSTITUTE BUS DRIVERS
(30) Hour Pre-Service Substitute Bus Driver Certification Class

Ascension Public Schools will conduct a thirty (30) hour pre-service class for anyone interested in becoming a certified substitute bus driver. Social Distancing measures will be implemented, and masks will be required.

The following schedule will be followed:

DATE: September 28, 29, 30 - October 1, 2

PLACE: APSB Distribution Center

932 West Orice Roth, Gonzales, LA 70737

TIME: 8:00 a.m. - 4:30 p.m.

Anyone interested in attending these classes to be certified as a substitute bus driver, please call Ascension Parish School Board Transportation Department at 225-391-7344 and give your name and telephone number to Jerril Bolding.

Have you completed the U.S. Census yet? Each person who goes uncounted costs Louisiana $2,291.

The 2020 Census count impacts the federal funds that communities receive each year for programs and services that are critical for schools, students, and younger children, such as:

*Special education, Head Start, after-school programs, and classroom technology.
*Food assistance, including free and reduced-price school lunches.
*Maternal and child health programs.

Complete it online in minutes: https://my2020census.gov/

post_text:
ASCENSION PUBLIC SCHOOLS TO RESUME NORMAL OPERATIONS ON FRIDAY AUG. 28, 2020

Donaldsonville, La. ‚Äì Ascension Public Schools will resume normal operations on Friday, Aug. 28, 2020, following closures from Hurricanes Marco and Laura this week.

Students will return to school as originally scheduled. That means all primary students will return to school, and middle and high school students on an alternating schedule should attend in person if they are in the first group, usually identified as ‚ÄúA‚Äù group for most schools. The second ‚ÄúB‚Äù group will remain virtual on Friday.

District staff spent much of today checking on school campuses, testing our infrastructure, and consulting with emergency officials. We are fortunate that Ascension Parish received very little damage from Hurricane Laura, but we continue to keep our neighbors to the west in our prayers. We will be looking at ways we can assist in their recovery in the days, weeks, and months ahead.

As always, for official decisions regarding school closures, please visit the district website, www.apsb.org.

###

post_text:
ASCENSION PUBLIC SCHOOLS TO CLOSE AUG. 24-25 DUE TO TROPICAL STORM MARCO

Donaldsonville, La. ‚Äì All schools and offices of Ascension Public Schools will close Monday, Aug. 24, 2020, and Tuesday, Aug. 25, 2020, due to the projected impacts of Tropical Storm Marco. These closures include the suspension of all instructional services, both in-person and online, so that staff and families can prepare for and respond to storm impacts. Twelve-month employees will remain on call during the closures.

District personnel are working closely with local and state emergency officials to monitor the path of Marco as well as the predicted path of Tropical Storm Laura. A decision on additional school closures will be made after monitoring the path of Tropical Storm Laura on Monday and Tuesday and consulting with emergency officials.

For official decisions regarding school closures, please visit the district website, www.apsb.org.

post_text:
CURBSIDE STUDENT MEALS: If your child is an online learner or is on a virtual day of an alternating schedule (middle & high school), you can pick up lunch from 10 a.m. until 11 a.m. daily at Lowery Elementary/Middle, Dutchtown High, East Ascension High, St. Amant High, and Sorrento Primary schools. Use this link to download and fill out the required Student Meal Request Form. Students do not need to be present, but you will need to hand this form in every day.

Students will pay according to their meal benefit status. Lunch accounts can be charged. You can pay in advance online at https://osp.osmsinc.com/AscensionLA/, using a check, or by cash with the exact amount. Our Child Nutrition staff will not be able to give change at the drive-thru line, so if you use cash that is not exact change, the balance will be added to the student's account.

Thank you for your patience and cooperation to make this go as smoothly as possible!

https://share.peachjar.com/flyers/1012169/districts/9625

The Ascension Parish School Board is asking voters to extend an existing 15.08 mills to fund designated construction projects and improvements across the district.

The proposal includes a much-needed new high school, updated classrooms, and athletic facilities, and other major improvements. The dedicated millage has supported capital improvements for 40 years.

Early voting begins this Saturday, July 25th and goes through August 8, except Sunday at the Donaldsonville and Gonzales Courthouses and Oak Grove Community Center

You can learn more online at www.apsb.org/2020bond

post_text: "The School Tools drive is a vital annual support of Ascension Public Schools as it provides classroom supplies directly to our schools. Not every student is in a position to afford supplies, and Volunteer Ascension works directly with our school counselors to make sure all items donated by our community go to those who need them," said Ascension Public Schools Superintendent David Alexander. "The support of our community through programs like School Tools is one of the strengths of our school system."

post_text: Congratulations to the St. Amant High #Classof2020!
shared_text:
St. Amant High School
May 6 at 5:48 PM ¬∑

It was an emotional but EXCITING sendoff for St. Amant High‚Äôs Class of 2020 today as our seniors celebrated their very last day of high school...the STA Way! Nearly 300 of our 486 seniors were the stars in their own Senior Parade that ran from the main campus to The Pit, where their class song was playing in the stadium. Teachers lined up with shakers and custom masks to send the seniors off to start the parade, while families and supporters waved signs and cheered on the students from their yards along the parade route. Principal Beth Templet said the entire event was planned as a special way to honor the graduating seniors, who began their high school years during the flood and found their senior year cut short by COVID-19. The event went very smoothly, thanks to tremendous help from the St. Amant Fire Department and the Ascension Parish Sheriff‚Äôs Office. Thanks to all the volunteers who helped make this a memorable day for our graduating seniors! Congratulations to our resilient Class of 2020! #thelastday...TheSTAWay #gatorpride #alwaysagator ‚ù§Ô∏èüêä‚ù§Ô∏è

post_text:
The week of May 4th through May 8th is Teacher Appreciation Week. Teachers work hard every day to help provide the best education to students everywhere. During these last two months, teachers had to adapt quickly to a new reality as they helped make the transition to online learning as easy as possible for students. So join us in helping make this the best Teacher Appreciation Week ever!

WAYS TO THANK A TEACHER:
*Write a letter to your teachers and mail it to your school.
*Make a card for your teachers and mail it to your school.
Post your thank you to social media using the taglines #ThankATeacher and #AscensionStrong.
*If you wish to give a teacher a gift, we recommend staying local by giving gift cards from local businesses.

We've included school addresses here for you. You can also find them on our website, www.apsb.org.

Ascension Parish Homeland Security (OHSEP)
April 26 at 11:24 PM ¬∑

This afternoon a full scale drill was conducted at Donaldsonville Primary School in preparation for the opening of the COVID-19 testing site tomorrow.

Monday the testing site will be open for Emergency Responders and Seniors 65 and older. Tuesday the testing site will open to the general public.

Quick Reminders:
What do you need to qualify? You need to be 18 years old and have an ID that shows you are a resident of Louisiana.
Yes! Assumption Parish and Iberville Parish residents will also be able to attend.
Cost? Free.
When? We will open the testing site Monday for Emergency Responders and our Seniors 65 and older. Tuesday - Saturday the site is open to the general public!
Time: 8:00 AM - 12:00 Noon
Where? Donaldsonville Primary School
Does my Doctor need to refer me? No.
No Medical referral needed.

Having testing available has been a top priority for President Cointment. Ascension Parish Office of Homeland Security has coordinated with many agencies so this testing site can open Monday.

https://youtu.be/r-wuWS5H2YQ

It's time to celebrate all of your many accomplishments and allow STA to take an opportunity to tell you goodbye and wish you well. The logos for Donaldsonville High School, Dutchtown High School, and East Ascension High School are trademark registered with the Louisiana Secretary of State Office and protected from unauthorized use in the categories of paper goods and printed matter, clothing, toys and sporting goods, and miscellaneous. Mar. 20, 2020

Dear Ascension Public Schools Families,

Our first week of school closures due to COVID-19 was filled with a lot of teamwork and heart as we started this transition to distance learning and "Grab & Go" student meals. We know not everything went perfectly, but we are all committed to working towards ensuring students have opportunities for high-quality learning each day.

Below is a video that highlights some of the great moments that took place this week and words of encouragement from you, our parents and guardians, for our employees. As we continue on this journey of unknowns, we want to strengthen our commitment to being your partner in this wonderful community. Together, we are #AscensionStrong!

Respectfully,

David Alexander
Superintendent
Ascension Public Schools

Music credit: www.bensound.com

Starting on Wednesday, Mar. 18, 2020, Ascension Public Schools will offer free curbside meal pickup for all students every weekday from 10:30 a.m. until 12:30 p.m.

Pickup locations will be at Donaldsonville High, Dutchtown High, East Ascension High and St. Amant High schools.

Hot lunches and pre-packaged breakfasts will be distributed at each high school to any child. Walk-up service is also available, but all must maintain proper social distancing.

shared_text:
OSP.OSMSINC.COM
BLUFF MIDDLE SCHOOL CHEER TRYOUTS

Bluff Middle School
February 17 at 3:55 PM ¬∑

We are very excited to announce our CHEER TRYOUTS for next school year at Bluff Middle will be on March 31st and April 1st. This will be the FIRST cheer squad at Bluff Middle School! Students must be in either 7th grade or 8th grade next school year to tryout and have completed a physical. Current Dutchtown Middle and Prairieville Middle students wishing to tryout can pick up a packet in the front office of your schools. Please return the completed packet to your current schools‚Äô front office by March 23rd.

The tryouts will be held at Dutchtown High School in the gym from 3:30pm to 6:00pm each day. There is a $10 fee for the tryout that must be paid online.
The link is https://osp.osmsinc.com/AscensionLA/BVModules/ProductTemplates/Bvc2013/Product.aspx?productid=BK016-1020

If your child is interested in tryouts, please join our Remind group for more information and updates. @bluffcheer

UPDATE: 10:30 a.m., Jan. 31, 2020
Dear Parents and Guardians,

Power has been restored at Gonzales Middle and East Ascension High. We are proceeding with a normal school day.

Special thanks to our faculty and staff for maintaining productive classes while the power was down.

---
ORIGINAL MESSAGE: 9:00 a.m., Jan. 31, 2020
Dear Parents and Guardians,

Gonzales Middle School and East Ascension High are experiencing power outages that are impacting areas in the City of Gonzales. Everyone is safe and school is proceeding with modifications.

We expect the power issues to be resolved shortly and plan to proceed with a normal day at both schools. We will keep you updated.

Gonzales Middle School Mighty Bulldogs
East Ascension High School

UPDATE: 10:30 a.m., Jan. 31, 2020
Dear Parents and Guardians,

Power has been restored at Gonzales Middle and East Ascension High. We are proceeding with a normal school day.

post_text:
Tonight, the Ascension Parish School Board recognized Central Middle students Evan Paternostro and Ashton Reider, as well as Lake Elementary Facility Manager Irma Willis and St. Amant Volunteer Fire Department Chief James LeBlanc for their courageous efforts during last night‚Äôs fire at Lake Elementary.

Evan and Ashton noticed the fire in a classroom while attending a basketball game at their rival school. They immediately notified an adult. Ms. Irma pulled the fire alarm that prompted an evacuation of the school, and the St. Amant, 5th Ward and Galvez-Lake fire departments were able to stop the fire in 15 minutes.

No one was injured and only one classroom was damaged. Thank you to these brave individuals, as well as the school leaders and coaches who calmly evacuated everyone.

School will resume tomorrow thanks to the hard work of many school and district staff. We are all counting our blessings!

Central Middle School was named a state winner in the Samsung Solve for Tomorrow contest. Over 2,000 public schools submitted entries into the competition which were narrowed to 300 state finalists from across the country. CMS was 1 of 5 state finalists & the Louisiana winner.

As a reward for being named a state finalist, STEM teacher Michelle Jones received a Samsung Galaxy tablet for her classroom. As a state winner, CMS will receive $15,000 in Samsung products and classroom resources. Her class will now compete to become a national finalist.

Central Primary Colts
December 9, 2019 at 7:16 PM ¬∑

Central Primary Food Drive
By Caden Louque

Central Primary‚Äôs November service project was a great success for our community. We collected food items for the Greater Baton Rouge Food Bank for two weeks. We had a competition between the boys and the girls on who could collect the most food items. It was a very close competition, but the girls took the lead with 1,792 food items and the boys 1,704 food items. That is a total of 3,496 food items! Our school has helped many families in our community to have the food they need for the holidays. Thank you for joining us in the fight against hunger!

We had a competition between the boys and the girls on who could collect the most food items. It was a very close competition, but the girls took the lead with 1,792 food items and the boys 1,704 food items. That is a total of 3,496 food items! Our school has helped many families in our community to have the food they need for the holidays. Thank you for joining us in the fight against hunger!

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians,

According to the Centers for Disease Control (CDC), Louisiana is experiencing the highest level of influenza activity in the country.

During the next week while students are on Thanksgiving Break, we have an opportunity to help stop the spread of illness. Our custodial staff will be making a concerted effort to deep clean all of our schools, including disinfecting hard surfaces such as desks and doorknobs.

This may also be a good time for you to wash jackets, hats, backpacks, lunchboxes, shoes, etc. For items that cannot be washed, you may want to wipe them down with disinfectant wipes.

Also, please use this chart as a reference to determine when a student should be kept home from school and when they can return.

Together, we can help keep all our children, teachers and staff healthy!

Regards,

David Alexander, Superintendent
ASCENSION PUBLIC SCHOOLS

post_text: National recognition for St. Amant High‚Äôs FFA!
shared_text:
St. Amant High School
November 1, 2019 at 4:09 AM ¬∑

St. Amant FFA members and their sponsors spent this week networking with peers from FFA chapters around the country, learning about new innovations and research in agriculture, celebrating their accomplishments, competing in various contests and engaging in a team service project as part of the 92nd National FFA Convention and Expo in Indianapolis.

Once again, it was a great year for St. Amant FFA! They were recognized as a top 10 in the nation Premier Chapter finalist in the ‚ÄúGrowing Leaders‚Äù category of the National Chapter Award for their work on a school-wide anti-vaping educational campaign and were also awarded 3-Star rankings in the National Chapter Award.

Congratulations to sponsors Mandy Delaune, Marcy Mahler and Tate Roussel and their FFA members for being recognized for the magnificent work you all do at our school and in the community! #livingtoserve #stamantffa

By federal regulations, school meals must adhere to a strict amount of calories, sodium and fat content. For example, saturated fat must be less than 10% of total calories averaged over the week. Additionally, half of the weekly grains in the school lunch and breakfast menus must be whole grain-rich.

One of our most popular items, the Breakfast Stick, includes a low fat sausage wrapped in a whole grain pancake. #JointheBreakfastClub

post_text:
Congratulations to former Dutchtown High School teacher Tabitha Vu for being named a Presidential Award Winner! She will travel to Washington, D.C. to receive an official certificate signed by the President of the United States in addition to a $10,000 award from the National Science Foundation. This is the second time a Dutchtown High School teacher has won this prestigious honor. The late Brenden Simoneaux was honored in 2015.

Read more about Ms. Vu here:
https://mailchi.mp/b657ac3ff708/ascensions-tabitha-vu-is-state-finalist-for-presidential-teaching-award?e=[UNIQID]

Yvette Knight Surla's special education class at Dutchtown Middle launched a new kindness initiative, called "Cup of Thanks." On certain days, they prepare coffee and hot chocolate for teachers and staff. This is made possible through a grant by the Joe W. and Dorothy Dorsett Brown Foundation and EATEL.

According to Surla, it is part of a national initiative to increase employment for people with intellectual and physical disabilities.

#CupOfThanks #Excellence #AscendingTogether
